    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen `foldexpr` is set to `v:lua.vim.treesitter.foldexpr()`, and the default SwapExists autocmd is disabled, `:edit`ing a file already open in another nvim instance multiple times causes treesitter highlighting to break.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Save the below config script as `minimal.lua`\n2. Run `nvim --clean -u minimal.lua minimal.lua`\n3. Open a second terminal window, without closing the first one\n4. Run `nvim --clean -u minimal.lua minimal.lua` again in the second terminal window\n5. Press `e` to Edit anyway\n6. Run `:e` and press `e` to Edit anyway\n7. Repeat 6 until the syntax highlighting in the file breaks, this usually happens on the second time for me. At this point, running `:lua vim.treesitter.stop()` brings back regex syntax highlighting and `:lua vim.treesitter.start()` disables it, but the treesitter-based highlighting is not enabled again.\n\n```lua\nvim.opt.foldmethod = \"expr\"\nvim.opt.foldexpr = \"v:lua.vim.treesitter.foldexpr()\"\n\nvim.api.nvim_del_augroup_by_name(\"nvim.swapfile\")\n\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nTreesitter highlighting should keep working.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.11.0-dev-1636+ge3e1c1e765\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nAlacritty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nAUR",
